node.title: The latest update on our AR Project House!

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Atomic Ranch on August 07, 2021. May be an image of furniture and kitchen.

node.text:
⁠
For Project House Austin designer Christine Turnkett of @breathedesign, her relationship with Scandinavian Modern started with Ikea and grew to become a major source of inspiration. Christine points to this semi-circular island as an instance of design’s potential to be more democratic. The original island in this home was square, but given the homeowners’ desire to host, Christine took cues from circular seating arrangements common in Scandinavian design and decided to make the island a half-moon shape to allow for and encourage conversation. Learn more of her design philosophy via the link in our bio. ⁠
⁠
Photo by Chase Daniel @thevuvobandit⁠
⁠
⁠

This Portland home features a central atrium which the homeowner used as a reading room. Robert Rummer built lots of houses in and around greater Portland. But it’s the modern Eichler cousins that people refer to when they talk about having a “Rummer.” Take a tour of this Portland gem via the link in our bio. ⁠
⁠
Photo by Jim Brown⁠

node.text:
Are you as crazy for cantilevers as we are? Built by a group of students from the University of Arkansas, this home was designed to be an affordable prefab structure. It was constructed in two different modules and combined onsite. By cantilevering the upper module, additional outdoor space is created, adding to the total living space of the home. Learn more about these types of structures via the link in our bio. ⁠
⁠
Image courtesy of @Dezeen.⁠
⁠

node.text:
This Palm Springs home was designed by architects Dan Palmer and William Krisel and built in 1963 by the Alexander Construction Company. Today, it's the home of Tom Dolle and George Waffle, who have filled the space with vibrant color. The house is an escape from the heat, but still invites the sun to illuminate the entire home. Take a tour via the link in our bio. ⁠
@runitbytom⁠
Photo by Bret Gum @gum_and_gummer⁠

node.text:
Futuro forsaken 💔⁠
In Royse, TX an abandoned Futuro sits on an overgrown lot covered in graffiti. Only 19 of these Futuro buildings are left standing in the United States. Some are lovingly preserved, while others stand out like eyesores—abandoned and covered in graffiti. Although brilliantly designed by Matti Suuronen in 1968, these transportable and energy efficient spaceship-like structures never "took flight." Learn more about their history via the link in our bio. ⁠
⁠
Photo by Dana Mauer.⁠

Learn more and check out the Palm Springs Futuro House at @thefuturohouse 
⁠

node.text:
For this kitchen remodel, the homeowner wanted a subtle nod to the Space Age. Enter ModCraft’s ‘Hexon’ tile in ‘Pacific Blue Glaze’. This is a 6-inch hexagonal tile with a bold atomic pattern that creates a 3D illusion when put together, resulting in a modern knit pattern-two distinct shapes can be seen in the pattern once installed. See more of this Mod-styled Phoenix condo via the link in our bio. ⁠
Photo by Landon Wiggs @wiggsphoto⁠
